The last minute: our cosmic visitor is the giant asteroid 2014 JO25
There are billions, perhaps more, of giant asteroids loose in the solar system, and they can have serious consequences if they collide.
These objects, which may have closed or open orbits left over from the formation of the Sun, can sometimes pass through the Earth.
The 650-meter-wide asteroid 2014 JO25 is one such visitor and will pass 1.75 million kilometers from Earth's closest point at 14:24 today.
We hear more of this kind of news every day.
The main reason for this is the improvement in observation techniques and instruments.
This allows us to identify smaller asteroids that have not been identified before.
Last January, for example, an asteroid the size of a bus passed within only half the distance between Earth and the Moon - about a quarter of a million miles.
And even more intriguing, the asteroid was detected only days before it passed.
So there could be other cosmic buses coming at us right now.
Think about it. What would you do if you were told that an asteroid 20 meters across was going to fall right into the middle of your neighborhood?
Actually, asteroids this size won't destroy your neighborhood, but it'll probably blow out the windows of all the buildings.
That's because of the shock waves from the asteroid that's about to explode in the atmosphere.
For example, the asteroid that hit Russia in 2013 was this big, and it shattered the windows of buildings in several cities.
But if you're in the vicinity of an asteroid that's 100 meters across, I recommend you go at least 50 kilometers beyond your vicinity.
Criteria such as the size of the asteroid and its angle of impact determine the depth of the crater and the damage that the impact will cause.
Let's take a look at a few scenarios from the European Space Agency's simulation.
If an asteroid 100 meters in diameter were to hit the Earth at an angle of 45 degrees at 60 km per second, it would form a crater about 250 meters deep and 1,200 meters wide.
The impact is equivalent to a magnitude 6 earthquake on the Richter scale, and you'll get third-degree burns even if you're 10 kilometers away from the impact point.
The ones 50 kilometers away will be waiting for shattered windows.
If an asteroid a mile in diameter hits, it's even more disheartening.
If such an asteroid were to hit Earth at the same angle and velocity, it would form a crater about 600 meters deep and 12 kilometers in diameter.
So a whole neighborhood turns into a crater and disappears in an instant.
The heat from the impact will cause you to suffer third-degree burns even if you're 100 kilometers from the point of impact.
The impact is equivalent to an earthquake of magnitude 8 on the Richter scale.
The damage of an asteroid depends not only on its chemical composition but also on the rock structure of the area it will hit.
The above values are based on the scenario of a hard rock-like asteroid falling into a region of conical rock.
If the asteroid is mostly iron, if it falls on a surface that has been cooled by lava, the crater will be three times bigger, and the resulting disaster will be twice as big.
66 million years ago, something much worse happened to the dinosaurs, and they were struck by an asteroid about 10 kilometers in diameter.
The asteroid impact has killed 75% of all land and sea creatures.
If an asteroid this big that wiped out the dinosaurs is targeting Earth, the safest option is to leave the planet.
Every day, tons of material falls from space.
Most of it burns up in the atmosphere.
Some meteorites that are big enough burn up in the atmosphere, causing flashes known to the public as stellar slips.
Let's end the summer with another piece of comfort.
Studies show that a giant asteroid is not expected to hit Earth in the next 300 to 400 years, causing severe damage.
As a species that lives an average of 70 years, I'm sure you're all a little relieved.
