The human rights group issued a travel advisory for Missouri.
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a travel advisory for people of color in Missouri due to the state's discriminatory policies and racial attacks.
The group's statement reads: "The State of Missouri, through the NAACP Travel Advisory Notice effective August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, visitors, and Missourians to exercise extreme caution and care when traveling from the state's northern tip to its southern tip, as noted there, due to recent suspicious, racially motivated events occurring across the state".
The NAACP said a new Missouri law making it difficult for people to win discrimination cases, as well as the state's law enforcement's disproportionately targeting of minorities, was effective in the group's issuance of this travel warning.
"There are human rights violations that people are experiencing.
They're stopped, they're beaten and they're killed because of the color of their skin", Missouri NAACP president Rod Chapel told the Kansas City Star.
"We're getting complaints at a rate we've never heard before".
This is the first time the association has issued a statewide warning.
The group cited the racial slurs against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee, as examples.
Earlier this year, Sanders was arrested by Missouri police after running out of gas while crossing the state and was found dead in suspicious circumstances.
The advisory also highlights a new report from the Missouri Attorney General's Office that shows black drivers in the state are 75 percent more likely to be stopped than white drivers.
"The advisory is for people to be alert and to warn their family, friends and coworkers about the possibility of being in Missouri", Chapel said.
"People should be prepared to bring bail money with them or to inform their relatives that they are going to be in this state".
In Missouri, according to the latest figures from the FBI's hate crime reporting program, there were 100 hate crimes in 2015, putting the state 16th in the nation for the number of hate crimes.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that makes it harder for a business to sue for discrimination when renting or renting a home.
Previously, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued travel advisories for Texas and Arizona after those states passed immigration enforcement laws that mandated local law enforcement to arrest people for immigration violations; the ACLU says this would increase enforcement based on race.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the Department of State for other countries, but recently advocacy groups have resorted to this practice in response to a number of laws and trends within the United States.
