A rare glimpse of daily life in the mountainous regions of Papua, a former Dutch colony that Indonesia absorbed in 1969, after a controversial referendum in which only 1,026 people aged 10 and over were forced to vote by raising their hands in public before the Allied invasion.
An existing movement of independence propaganda against the Dutch government quickly directed its anger at the Jakarta government, which maintained tight control over the region, banning foreign journalists or rights watchdog organizations.
In 2003, the region was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent Papua New Guinea occupying the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is desolate; the journey here involves a 90-minute flight from the regional capital of Jayapura to Nabire and a five-hour car ride in a rented car with a stomach-churning stomach.
There is no public transport.
The 19,000-seat belt contains wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, rusted iron roofs transformed by rust into various shades of yellowish brown.
Let journalists alone, very few Indonesians have traveled here and almost no foreigners have traveled here.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Mee Pago Papuans worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
"We are not used to wearing these clothes", says Degei, referring to her brightly colored, hand-woven wrap, dark shirt, and glittering skirt.
"We used to wear only leaves on our bodies".
Papua is the poorest region in Indonesia, with 28 percent of the population living below the poverty line and the worst infant mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it's also the gold of Indonesia.
Grasberg, the largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is located just 60 miles from Paniai, a mountainous area the size of New Jersey and home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined approximately $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper from here.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in timber reserves.
Yet, for the Papuans, it is this wealth, a source of misery, that keeps Indonesia's powerful military a stranglehold.
A 2005 New York Times investigation reports that Freeport paid about $20 million to local military personnel and units between 1998 and 2004, including up to $150,000 in bribes to a single officer.
The call for greater autonomy from the Papuans threatens this golden egg-laying hen and ruthlessly tramples on its rights.
According to rights activists, since 1969 more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by the Indonesian army, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
The mass killings in the highlands of Papua in the 1970s amounted to genocide, according to the Asian Commission on Human Rights.
Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region last year alone.
The Brisbane Archdiocese's 2016 "We Will Lose Everything" report includes testimony from the previous year, including extrajudicial executions, torture (where rape and electrocution are particularly popular according to another report) and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to count the number of victims because there are incidents every week", says Andreas Harsono, Indonesia researcher for Human Rights Watch.
Pressures were heightened as Papua's resources brought settlers from elsewhere in Indonesia.
The region's population of 3.5 million is 83% Christian, but the demographics are changing as Muslim immigrants from Indonesia's populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi arrive for economic purposes.
Javalí warung buffet sells gado-gado, which is served with peanut sauce mixed with fried chicken and vegetables.
The locals are struggling to compete.
"The migrants sell chicken and vegetables at cheaper prices than the local Papuans in the traditional markets", explains Abeth You, 24, a native of Paniai who moved to the regional capital Jayapura for work.
"This has caused the local Papuans, the Papuan mama-mas (women) to lose the market".
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, better known as Jokowi, promised during his 2014 election campaign to address inequality and rights abuses in Papua.
The former carpenter, on his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta, took the vote of 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Panaia.
But little has changed in Papua, and today the local people feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi in the expectation that he would fulfill our hope that justice would be restored", You said.
In fact, Paniai experienced its worst just two months after Jokowi took office in October.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were singing Christmas songs outside a bonfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on motorcycles tore through the dark.
The frightened children told them they had to turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers resented their manner, and according to local priest Yavedt Tebai, he later returned with four soldiers.
Victims and witnesses said that the soldiers, who were drunk, chased the group and beat them with the butt of their rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot at the group of children.
One of the boys, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was so badly beaten that he lapsed into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby government election commission building was set on fire, and the next day, the violence escalated.
About 1,000 Papuans, men, women and children, gathered at a football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They carried traditional hunting bows and performed the waita dance of the Mee Pago tribe of Papua (running in a circle and mimicking the song of birds).
Some protesters started throwing stones at the police and military garrison.
As the nerves grew more tense, orders were sent over the internal radio to the soldiers: "If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them dead". An official document seen by TIME, but not disclosed to local media, said:
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of the Kego Koto neighborhood in Enarotali, saw the approaching danger and urged the crowd to return home and appeal for calm.
No one was going to listen.
"I turned around and was hit by a bullet in my left wrist", he told TIME on the front porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired it, but he says the bullet came from a military era.
"It was crowded, there was a lot of shooting", he adds.
According to his cousin, who witnessed the attacks, local resident Alfius Youw was shot three times.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him", he told TIME, gloomily.
"I saw her die... and I kissed her".
Papua Police Chief Inspector General Yotje Mende told reporters that his officers had only "taken the station to safety" because the station was under attack.
Papua police spokesman Branch Manager Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015: "When people threaten to kill us, we have to defend ourselves".
"This is a matter of life and death".
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
News of the deaths reached Jakarta only the next day.
Jokowi made a stirring speech three weeks later in Jayapura, expressing sympathy with the victims' families and promising to resolve historical abuses in Papua.
"I want this case solved immediately so that it doesn't happen again".
In October 2016, Security Minister Wiranto said that a non-judicial mechanism had been established for historical human rights violations.
But the excuses began almost immediately.
"Most of the attacks were long ago.
Some in the '90s, some in the early 2000s.
The point is that we are committed to resolving these violations, but there are processes that we have to go through".
Speaking to TIME on June 5, Wiranto backtracked, saying there was no plan to set up a grievance mechanism in Papua.
Instead, he said, "It's all going to be solved by law".
Wiranto, who accused the UN of "crimes against humanity" involving more than 1,000 deaths during East Timor's bloody independence vote in 1999, said 11 human rights violations in Papua, including the Paniai incident, had already been solved.
The families of the Paniai victims have met such claims with bitter skepticism.
"I have been admitted to four appointments in the past three years, but no progress has been made", says Johannes.
"I was tired".
Years later, he says he still lives in fear.
"I'm scared", he says.
"I'm afraid of being arrested by the army, afraid of being shot".
His brother Yacobus reiterates the view that people in Paniai are afraid to discuss the matter.
He says he was beaten by the soldier after helping to bury four of the victims.
"After I buried the bodies, the soldier came looking for me".
The attacks have not stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police opened fire on villagers in Deiyai district, Paniai's neighbour.
During the clash between the villagers and the manager of a construction company who refused to help take a man to the hospital who was unconscious, one person died and 17 people were injured, including children.
Ravianus Douw, 24, drowned in a nearby lake while fishing, died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company's construction office.
The police said that the villagers threw stones at the officers, who responded by firing warning shots.
But locals say the mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) opened fire on the crowd and killed someone.
"We were very panicked, afraid of revenge", Dominggu Badii, 29, who lived near the hospital and witnessed the treatment of the wounded, told TIME.
"I've been hiding in my house for two days".
The parliament of Deiyai called for the officials involved to be held accountable and for the mobile police brigade to be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a problem area for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development fuels discontent among the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribal peoples who live scattered across Papua's green highland heartland.
Many joined the rebel army, the Free Papua Movement (OPM), which claimed to protect the rights of Papuans by carrying out random attacks and kidnapping raids on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM leaders, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya, are from Paniai.
In response, thousands of people in Paniai have been arrested and arbitrarily detained by the military in recent years under the pretext of "protecting national sovereignty".
Some of them never see each other again.
Among the people of Papua, Paniai is known as "a tragic and forgotten place".
Poverty feeds discontent.
The little rice that is sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the Indians to buy.
Bread is unattainable.
The people here grow everything they eat: mainly the note, but also some fruits and vegetables.
Farming is the work of women who can support themselves with four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually keep most of the crop for the family, and sell the rest at the local market.
10 of them are only 10,000 Indonesian rupiah (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequalities grew between the indigenous Papuans and the new immigrants who arrived in greater numbers since the opening of new air routes to Nabire Airport.
And the jobs that are scarce usually go to immigrants who are better educated and richer.
The Papuans rarely have the capital or the skills to run their businesses competitively.
John Gobai, chairman of the Panai tribal council, says, "Young people are not interested in staying in the village because there is no work or money here".
Tecrit is keeping the world's eyes off of Papua.
Moreover, the journalistic restrictions for international media remain strict.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were deported from Papua for "lack of coordination with relevant agencies", despite being granted a rare video permit.
According to Phelim Kine, Asia Deputy Director of Human Rights Watch, Jokowi's campaign promises to lift restrictions on reporting and development to increase transparency have not been fulfilled.
In a statement, he said: "Foreign journalists trying to cover the troubled eastern provinces of Papua and West Papua face new dangers: visa denials and blacklisting".
The lack of press censorship means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is mostly limited to Papua's immediate neighbors.
In March, six Pacific nations (Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands) urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread violations" in Papua, including the Panaia attacks.
The same countries have historically supported the OPM.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesperson Arrmanatha Nasir ignored the group's claims, telling journalists in Jakarta that "the democratic system is still in place in Indonesia and there is a free media so it is difficult to cover up evidence in human rights cases".
The local people want more foreign government to be involved.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by the country's human rights envoy Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, according to a source who attended the meeting and did not want to be named, the local people broke the silence with pleas of "We want freedom".
Indonesia has one more presidential election in 2019, but Papuans say it's unlikely they'll vote for Jokowi again.
"Jokowi is a person of good intentions, but surrounded by people who were involved in the Paniai attack", says Gobai, the tribal council chairman.
Jokowi wants the people of Paniai to know that, apart from living under the looming threat of a tyrannical soldier, they are wallowing in poverty with meager education and health services.
Gobai says that the Paniai people, like other Papuans, see their votes as a "loan" to Jokowi to pay him back.
"They don't need money, they just want justice".
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai attack have taken a last symbolic act of defiance: burying the body of a victim in a field directly opposite the police and military station.
Knowing that justice can never be served, they will at least ensure that those responsible do not forget their crimes.
"A member of our family was killed", Yacobus says, his head bowed.
"What else can we do?"
The fire has engulfed Dubai's 'Meshal' skyscraper for the second time.
In Dubai, a fire on Friday gutted the world's tallest residential towers, forcing hundreds of residents to flee the 337-meter, 79-story building.
This is the second major fire in two years that has quickly spread to a tall building called the Torch Tower.
The building was evacuated, no injuries were reported, and no explanation was given as to the cause of the large fire.
"We were sleeping and we woke up to the fire alarm, people were screaming.
We ran down the stairs and it took us about 10 minutes to get to the 50th floor", a resident who gave his name as George told Reuters.
Dubai's civil defense authorities said fire crews extinguished the large fire at around 4 am local time (00:00 GMT) and were cooling the building.
The government has stated that they are trying to provide shelter for those affected.
This incident could re-raise questions about the safety of materials used on the exterior of tall buildings around the world.
The Torch Authority's investigation following the 2015 fire found that most of the damage was to the cladding, the outer panels used for decoration and insulation.
In the United Kingdom, police said they believe the insulation and coating panel system on London's Grenfell Tower, where 80 people died, may have contributed to the rapid spread of the fire there in June.
The gospel of 'social help' to more than 4 thousand chronic patients
The Ministry of Family and Social Policies will launch a social assistance program for poor citizens and their families who are struggling with chronic diseases, and 4,300 tuberculosis and SSPE patients will benefit in the first phase.
The Ministry plans to provide monthly support to patients above two thirds of the minimum wage with its aid program, and will also provide regular psychosocial support.
According to the information, the details and implementation principles of the "New Social Assistance Program for Families Struggling with Chronic Diseases" that started to work a while ago with the instruction of the Minister of Family and Social Policies Fatma Betul Sayan Kaya have become known.
The social assistance program, which was launched in cooperation with the Ministry of Health to support citizens who are struggling with chronic diseases and who are experiencing economic and psychological difficulties, is also the first in the world in many respects.
The Ministry, which has completed all the preparations necessary for the launch of the program, will provide families with regular psychosocial support through the social assistance program, not only cash.
This is to ensure that poor citizens and their families who have chronic illnesses and continue their treatment processes at home are not left alone, both materially and spiritually.
According to the studies, in the first stage, poor citizens who are struggling with SubAcute Sclerosing Panencephalitis (SSPE), a brain disease caused by tuberculosis and the measles germ, will be provided with regular psychosocial and cash support under the new social assistance program.
And in the later stages of the program, it will be extended to help poor citizens who are struggling with other rare and life-threatening diseases.
In addition to the support, which is planned to be paid at a rate of more than two-thirds of the minimum wage, additional payments may be made to tuberculosis patients who cannot afford medical care, are bed-dependent or whose home living conditions need to be improved.
To be eligible for the allowance, the household must have a per capita monthly income of less than two thirds of the net monthly minimum wage.
Also, citizens with SSPE must have a health board report prepared according to the procedures and principles specified in the "Regulation on the Measurement, Classification and Health Board Reports for Disabled Persons".
