EPA Chairman Pruitt has refused to delay the Obama-era emissions cuts.
A day after being sued by 15 states, Environmental Protection Agency Chairman Scott Pruitt has backed away from the Obama-era law that reduced emissions of dirty fumes.
Pruitt represented change in that his organization was more responsive to the needs of state environmental regulators than past administrations.
He never mentioned the legal challenge to his previous position in a federal high court.
The states in question are beginning to meet the 2015 ground-level ozone standards by October 1, the end of the period.
Pruitt announced in June that he would delay compliance for a year to give his organization more time to work on the plan and avoid "interfering with local decisions or impeding economic growth".
Pruitt, who was the state attorney general of Oklahoma before being appointed by President Donald Trump, had long served as a trusted ally against stricter environmental regulations.
Since coming to Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly moved to block or delay regulations that the chemical and fossil fuel industries oppose.
Wednesday's sudden change is the latest legal defeat for Pruitt's agenda to reverse the arrangement.
Last month, a federal high court in Washington ruled that the EPA administrator had overstepped his authority to try to delay an Obama administration law requiring oil and gas companies to monitor and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday night, Pruitt argued that the backsliding in ozone standards only strengthened the EPA's commitment to working with states to meet the new standards on time and through complex processes.
Pruitt, who has sued the EPA more than a dozen times in his previous work, said, "Under previous administrations, the EPA frequently failed to meet deadlines for rulings, waited to be sued by activist groups and others, and agreed to settle disputes to set timelines for rulings".
"We don't believe in settling by litigation, and we take due dates seriously.
We also take the law and its authority seriously".
However, the EPA's statement stated that Pruitt may at some point once again exercise "the power of deferral and all other powers legally available" to ensure that regulations are "supported by sound policies and the best available information".
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader rewrite of the ozone laws.
A House bill passed last month seeks to delay the implementation of 2015 laws by at least eight years.
The measure has not yet been brought to the Senate for a vote.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led the coalition of states suing the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue legal pressure.
Schneiderman said, "The EPA's reversal of its decision following our lawsuits is a significant victory for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans who are directly affected by the filthy smoke that is pouring into their communities".
The lawsuit was filed in New York by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington and the District of Columbia.
Ground-level ozone is produced when common pollutants are released by automobiles, power plants, oil refineries, chemical plants, and other sources that react with sunlight in the atmosphere.
The resulting foul smoke can cause severe respiratory problems in a vulnerable group of people and contribute to thousands of premature deaths every year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists have applauded Pruitt's surprise reversal.
Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity said: "It is disturbing that it takes so much pressure to get this sensible step from someone who is responsible for protecting the air we breathe".
"We must continue to fight against the Trump administration's ideological battle to pander to environmental polluters and interest groups".
