In April 1946, a high court ruling allowed black citizens in Georgia to vote for the first time in a primary election later that summer.
According to the FBI, around the same time as the election, black partner Roger Malcom stabbed white landowner Barnett Hester in a fight over what appeared to be a woman.
Brooks testified that the word in town was that Hester was sleeping with Malcolm's wife, Dorothy, and that the baby she was carrying was not her husband's.
