New results of Sweden's illiteracy age assessment test have been released
In Sweden, the latest results of a new medical age assessment test for refugees show that more than 80 percent of the subjects are over the age of 18, but not everyone trusts the test.
The Swedish National Agency for Forensic Medicine and Pharmaceuticals (Rättsmedicinalverket) started testing earlier this year.
The tests were designed to make the age estimates more accurate during the asylum process after criticism of the Swedish Migration Agency's (Migrationsverket) failure to assess the exact age of some of the refugees who claimed to be underage.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6880 cases to the test and the Forensic Medicine and Pharmaceutical Directorate has now released the results of 2481 of the tests from the period from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (of the 2002 figure) were judged to be 18 or over, and in 25 cases the Office of Forensic Medicine judged the subject to be "probably 18 or over".
In 432 cases, the result was that the person was "probably under 18".
The tests were only done in cases where the person's age was suspect.
According to Johan Göransson of the Department of Forensic Medicine, the results are consistent with the past months.
"We don't see a big difference in the statistics from last month, the numbers are pretty consistent", he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases that are judged to be over 18 years old does not necessarily mean that refugees are lying about their age.
The department explained the results of 581 tests and said there were 442 cases "where the examined individuals were shown to be 18 years of age or older".
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the results of 581 cases that were reported, it found that 243 cases openly declared that they had turned 18 this year.
The medical age assessment method, which involves taking X-rays of the teeth of 20-year-olds and doing MRI scans of the knee joints, then having them analyzed by dentists and radiologists, is being criticized in some circles.
One of the skeptics is endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, whose work assesses the biological maturity of people who enter the nebula earlier or later than normal.
"I have reason to think about it, and I think that's not the kind of measurement that should be used.
It's very suspicious to judge biological age that way.
If we can't say for sure, we shouldn't pretend it is".
However, Göransson of the Office of Forensic Medicine and Pharmaceuticals defended the accuracy of the tests: "You could say that the risk of a child being wrongly judged to be an adult in general is small.
The greatest risk is that the person is just under 18, and in this case the risk is about 10 percent".
