How will the financial rules of football affect Neymar's trip to Paris?
The rules to prevent European football clubs from spending unlimited money will not prevent Neymar's world record transfer from Barcelona, Spain to Paris Saint-Germain, France.
The prestigious Champions League tournament has the power to ban teams from the UEFA, the governing body of European football, to Paris Saint-Germain.
The Financial Fair Play rules, imposed by UEFA in 2011, mean that PSG will eventually have to show that it financed Neymar's transfer without incurring huge losses.
Barcelona was paid 222 million euros ($262 million) just to buy the Brazilian out of contract, and Neymar will command a salary that will bring in tens of millions of dollars a year.
Some of the financial aspects of Neymar's move to France are:
Given the money the team gets from the energy-rich Qatari family, PSG could certainly afford to sign Neymar and add him to their galaxy of other stars.
Clubs are allowed to spend a lot of money to buy players, but they have to balance it with legitimate sources of income, provided they get to the top of their football-related business.
The FFP was designed by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA president in 2007.
The former Frenchman believed that clubs that incurred huge debts in the pursuit of success were effectively cheating, and were at risk of bankruptcy if banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, FFP began to monitor club losses instead of focusing on debts.
The change meant that the model that Roman Abramovich first used at Chelsea in 2003 (buy a club with potential, spend heavily to improve the team, and build a global brand) was transformed into a more challenging venture.
In the three-year FFP evaluation period, which runs until 2018, clubs can suffer losses of up to 30 million euros.
Despite Platini's unfair removal from the presidency in 2015, his successor at UEFA, Aleksander Ceferin, remains adamant that the overspending should be stopped.
Andrea Traverso, who runs FFP at UEFA, told the Associated Press last week: "FFP is definitely not dead and we will definitely strengthen the rules by moving forward".
Although PSG will pay Neymar's purchase price in full, it may spread the amount over the contract for accounting reasons.
Neymar signed a five-year deal, so the transfer fee can be shown as a cost of 44.4 million euros in the annual accounts for the next five years.
The first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014 saw the most severe sanctions applied to Manchester City, which is owned by PSG and Abu Dhabi.
PSG was fined 60 million euros ($82 million at the time), which was later reduced to 20 million euros, and ordered to limit the Champions League squad to 21 players instead of the usual 25 for the 2014-2015 season.
UEFA is on the lookout for clubs that may try to defraud financial regulators by inflating their revenues through companies linked to the club's owners.
Although a Qatari company may sponsor PSG, UEFA will not allow it to be counted as legitimate income if the value of the sponsorship is considered to exceed standard market values.
This was the case in 2014, when UEFA ruled that the sponsorship of Qatar Tourism Authority for PSG was overstated.
It was reported that part of Neymar's earnings from PSG could come through payments to Qatar's 2022 World Cup organising committee.
But PSG and Qatar have denied that Neymar will be a World Cup ambassador in 2022, and such a move could easily be exposed by UEFA organisers.
The sanctions imposed on PSG in the past mean that UEFA will be more careful against attempts to circumvent the rules.
According to sources on Tuesday, UEFA is not in pre-emptive talks with PSG over Neymar's transfer.
They spoke to The Associated Press on condition of anonymity, as they were not authorized to discuss the situation of PSG.
Recently published figures show that PSG made a profit of 542.4 million euros in 2015-16 with a turnover of more than 10 million euros.
The accounts for the last financial year have not been published yet.
PSG expects Neymar's arrival to contribute to their sponsorship deals, gift and shirt sales.
The club expects the fee to increase by at least 30% once the signing is done.
The Spanish league, clearly upset by the departure of one of football's greatest players, tried to block Neymar's departure by claiming that PSG had violated the FFP.
La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS that Qatar is the absolute owner of PSG, saying "This is a clear case of 'financial doping' with the club and the state".
