The Bank of England will keep interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce that interest rates will not change soon after it reduced its speculation that slow economic growth and a move to inflation would be a boost.
The Bank of England warned that economic growth would continue to be "slow" as they kept interest rates steady, along with shrinking family incomes.
The bank's Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted 6-2 to keep interest rates at 0.25 percent, so fewer members have called for increases this month after slow economic growth weakened support for growth.
The Bank raised its growth forecast in its quarterly inflation report to 1.7% in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018, and warned that household incomes would continue to contract, with inflation still expected to rise to close to 3% in the spring.
However, he indicated that interest rate hikes are needed to rein in Brexit-fuelled inflation over the next few years, and said borrowing costs could remain higher than expected in financial markets.
Members also voted to roll back part of the massive post-Brexit economic recovery package launched a year ago.
The bank will end its Periodic Funding Scheme, which offers cheap financing to banks, from next February, but said it expected to provide a further £15 billion (£115 billion in total) under the scheme.
Minutes after the interest rate decision was made, the bank said: "The central estimate of the MPC is that the gross domestic product (GDP) is slowing down in the short term as the narrowing of real household incomes continues to be a burden on consumption".
On interest rates, he stressed that "some tightening in monetary policy" may be necessary to mitigate inflation and that the market would be "a bit higher" than expected.
Markets are still predicting the first rise will be in the third quarter of next year and another in 2020.
But the bank stresses that any increase will be "step by step" and "limited".
According to the May projections, the bank's reduced growth forecasts for this year and next year are 1.9% and 1.7%, respectively.
The bank maintains its forecast of 1.8% in 2018.
Sterling fell against the dollar and euro following the news.
The pound fell by 0.5% to 1.31 US dollars and by 0.4% to 1.11 euros.
The decision not to change came after the latest growth figures, which were disappointing with GDP growing by 0.2% in the previous three months compared to 0.3% in the second quarter, softened expectations of a multiple increase.
Growth will probably remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, but according to the bank, it will begin to show a slight increase towards the end of the year.
While the bank says the downturn will get worse before it gets better, the latest inflation report leaves households, hit by soaring inflation and meager wage increases, with little to rejoice about.
The bank said that monetary policy would "not prevent" income shocks in the next few years, but that it expected wages to improve "significantly" towards the end of its three-year forecast.
The rise in demand for British goods as a result of the weak pound will help the economy by offsetting some of the declining consumer spending.
The decision comes a year after the pound was voted down to 0.25% in August, following the shock EU referendum.
The bank estimates that it will likely take four years for this to have a full impact on prices and the economy.
The bank's latest interest rate decision was preceded by a call for an interest rate increase that was due to the rising inflationary pressures on struggling households and a call by three policymakers for an increase to 0.5% in July.
Inflation has fallen from 2.9% in July to 2.6% last month, but the bank says this is expected and will rise again in the coming months.
The bank said the excess was "totally" due to the weak pound against its own 2% target.
Andrew Montlake, a director at Coreco Mortgage Brokers, said: "Given recent declines in interest rates, the mortgage market will once again become more competitive with lenders demanding that business be done and the year be closed positively.
The market looks good in re-mortgages, especially for those nearing the end of their existing contracts, with many free options and low interest rates, becoming more popular than ever".
The NHS is going to prescribe the controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people.
Following a fight in the High Court over the funding of the drug in the NHS, patients will be able to access 'transformative' HIV prevention treatment from September.
NHS England has announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a pill taken before sex that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection by around 86 per cent in high-risk people, will be provided by health services to an estimated 10,000 people in a three-year pre-trial.
The Supreme Court's decision last year, following the Court of Appeal's approval, agreed to fund the trial, saying that the NHS had the power to pay for PrEP, despite claims that local authorities were funding it.
The move, announced on Thursday, was hailed by NHS England chief Simon Stevens as a 'new and serious intervention', while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described it as a 'turning point'.
Sexual health clinics in Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to register for the public, with more clinics joining in October to be fully implemented across the UK by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a series of HIV medications that reduce the risk of contracting HIV before sex.
Trials have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission among those at risk of infection.
Getting PrEP before sex means that a person has enough of the medication to prevent HIV infection from taking root in their body.
These drugs can be taken every day or up to two hours before sex.
Those eligible for treatment are gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and HIV-positive partners who have not been successfully treated.
Clinics will identify eligible participants to be included in the trial, including men, women, transgender individuals, and those whose partners are not known to have HIV cases controlled with antiretroviral therapy.
People living in the UK and registered with a general practitioner may also register for potential participation at participating local sexual health clinics.
The programme will cost £10 million and NHS England has signed a deal to supply the drugs this week through a proposed international tender.
The trial is designed to assess the full potential of PrEP by gathering clinical evidence on how PrEP is targeted, administered and administered at large scale.
Mr Stevens said: 'This new and serious intervention will contribute to a large-scale and increasingly successful effort to prevent HIV.
This is another milestone in my thirty years of progress in addressing one of the major health problems of humanity.'
Deborah Gold, chair of the National Aids Trust, said: 'This is a milestone in the fight against HIV.
If it's targeted correctly at those who need it and those who are at risk, PrEP offers the potential to transform the HIV epidemic in the UK.
Starting in September, people at high risk for HIV in the UK will have access to a new and powerful tool, through this trial funded by the NHS, that is truly personalized and non-negotiable with a partner, that will lead to the healing of many lives.
We welcome this announcement".
Ian Green, chairman of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: 'The priority now is to ensure that the trial is rapidly rolled out nationwide and that no one at risk of HIV is left behind.
With the PrEP trial now available, we are on track to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV.'
Shadow public health minister Sharon Hodgson said: 'We welcome the start of the PrEP trial, and it has been delayed by months of delays and then government backtracking.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the spread of this life-changing infection.
The trial will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
Now it's important that this trial be available nationwide as soon as possible to protect people who are exposed to HIV and to bring us one step closer to ending the spread of HIV in our communities.
