Erfan had to think creatively to solve the problem.
"The steel skeleton is quite complex", he explains.
"We had to arrange the gaps so that they could collapse without the need to bend down on top of each other.
It was not just a simple platform, but the steel would be bent so that it would be at the right height for the function above or below".
This arrangement, with many additional dramas, allowed Erfan to have two full-size rooms on top of each other.
For the hanging floor, the old-style copper light window from Retrouvius overlooks the magnificent living space below.
The mirrored gold furniture, the silver accents and the old-style Serge Mouille lighting all define the style of the design.
The use of mirrors plays a role in the addition of space, space and light.
Mirrors at either end of the short corridor make it look longer.
The mirrored guardrail in the kitchen gives the impression of a window opening into another room.
The tracked units provide a hiding place for Joanne's entire forklift and shearing equipment.
The beauty of the living room, which creates a more spectacular sense of space, is that you can close the kitchen when it's not in use.
Kitchens open and close, they're not new.
What's unique about this is that it has a garage-style door that can be moved up.
"We used a bit of engineering on this one", explains Erfan, the steel-reinforced polished MDF door.
"It's balanced in weight so it slides really easily when you push the door up".
With the wise use of space and storage, Joanne gained an additional 16 square feet, an extra bedroom, and an improved seating plan.
"At the end of the day, it's the seat that you sell, or the value of your property", says Erfan.
"As a request, a realtor will enter and make a calculation based on the area of the session".
