The brothers are fighting over a $500 million real estate empire.
Forty years after their Italian family founded the dynasty, two brothers are at war over one of Victoria's largest real estate empires, worth over $500 million.
Former Carlton Football Club director and contractor Colin De Lutis lives in a mansion in Toorak, three doors down from his younger brother Paul, who has taken himself to the High Court over how to divide up property and business assets.
Paul had been trying to get out of the family business since 2014, but there was a fierce debate in the High Court about the break-up.
The brothers, along with their mother, Anna, own 38 properties worth more than half a billion dollars, accumulated since they bought a store on Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans and grew it into a chain of 160 retail outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
That money was invested in property, and De Lutis' portfolio now includes city offices, Brunswick and Sorrento development sites, Gold Coast and Mt Buller apartments, and suburban shopping malls.
Under an agreement with his late father, Colin (described by Paul as "a key driving force and a dominant personality" in the De Lutis family) owns two-thirds of the company's assets, and Paul one-third.
A court filing says that means Colin owns $316 million and Paul owns $176 million worth of property.
For Paul, the division of property and cash is a contentious issue.
In his first sworn testimony in court in 2015, he wrote, "The divisions proposed by Colin left him with what I have always called the best of properties".
Last Friday, after many failed mediations, the first High Court hearing was held.
The brothers are also fighting over who will control the current business; Paul claims Colin has left him out of the loop.
Colin insists that's not true, but he does accuse Paul of mismanaging some of the properties.
Colin, in his initial affidavit, said he hoped to resolve the dispute.
"My Italian roots dictate to me that family is the most important priority".
The costs of the case are mounting, with hundreds of pages of affidavits, emails and best-in-class lawyers like Allan Myers, QC, and senior legal counsel hired by both sides, recorded by firms including Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late husband Luigi were an Italian immigrant family who had been running grocery and deli stores since the late 1950s and had bought a store in Brunswick in the early 1970s.
They pawned their assets to buy the Collingwood estate where Colin opened the family's first jeans store.
Colin says that he started Westco there "in my final years at the high school, when Paul was a little boy, about 10 years old".
Anna De Lutis herself and Luigi, who died in 2012, say they hoped to leave their property to their sons in a friendly manner.
"Luigi often told me that he never wanted the brothers to be in court", she wrote.
The other two brothers Mark and Luke are no longer part of the De Lutis group of companies; Colin says Mark was paid $10 million and Luke $26 million when he left.
Both Luke and Mark, Paul says, were "displeased with the terms of their financial separation".
According to the 2015 biography of television star best friend Eddi McGuire, Colin tried to remain unnoticed, despite being a former AFL club board member.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul De Lutis and their lawyers on Friday.
Colin just texted back saying, "I can't say any more because the case is in court".
"It is very, very sad that my brother Paul has chosen to sue me and drag our family name into the courts".
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in a court filing that he was trying to comply with his brother's demands.
"Our father would not want Paul and I to fall into the current conflict", he said, adding that he was "still hopeful of a solution".
On Friday, that hope seems to have been lost.
Colin wrote, "Our problem will be solved by the courts in the near future".
Trump's new personal secretary is planning to restrict the president's media diet.
Others have tried and failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly really can do it.
If so, it'll be the first.
Politico reports that the new White House special counsel will restrict the flow of information (including news media reports) to President Trump in hopes of holding his boss more steady.
A little something from reporter Josh Dawsey:
"New White House private secretary John F. Kelly, meeting with senior staff on his first day in office, summed up a fundamental problem that President Donald Trump plans to solve with the White House: bad information getting into the hands of the president.
Kelly explained that information had to flow through the staff, whether it was on paper or in briefings, because the president could make better decisions when he was well informed.
Kelly's diagnosis makes a lot of sense, but others have tried to humiliate Trump by controlling the media diet, and failed.
President Trump's relationship with television goes back decades, and he's still in the White House, watching TV.
A former campaign adviser, Sam Nunberg, told Politico in February, "If Aday Trump is upset that he's not fairly represented in the media, it was productive to show him that he's fairly represented in persuadable media organizations".
Tara Palmeri of Politico wrote at the time, "According to six campaign officials, the key to keeping Trump's Twitter habit in check was to ensure that his personal media consumption contained a steady stream of praise".
I'll take that.
But the idea that Trump's Twitter habit is "under control" at any given time is ridiculous.
Maybe these campaign workers know something the rest of us don't, like that Trump's tweets would be far more provocative if they weren't the ones who intervene.
We'll probably never know anything about the tweets that Trump didn't send.
If his men were able to get him out of harm's way a few times, then their efforts were worth it.
But no one could stop Trump from creating controversy.
Part of the problem was that the White House was made up of competing factions, people who were trying to advance their own agenda with material that they were offering to Trump, which could be trusted or untrusted, and people who were promoting their own worldview.
Politico reported in May that throughout this story, advisors have been strategically tending to convey dubious information to the president.
An example, detailed by reporter Shane Goldmacher, was this:
"Current and former Trump officials say Trump has reacted angrily to negative press reports, particularly leaks that have had a negative effect, and has been obsessed with finding out where they originated.
That's what happened in late February when someone leaked to the president a printed copy of an article from GotNews.com, the website of internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson, accusing his private secretary Katie Walsh of being "the source behind a series of leaks" in the White House.
It didn't matter if Johnson was permanently banned from Twitter for harassment or for providing no concrete evidence or for making false accusations in the past and then turning away from them.
Trump read the article and started asking staff questions about Walsh".
Goldmacher added that then-Private Secretary Reince Priebus and White House Staff Secretary Rob Porter "attempted to put in place a system that handled and documented the papers that Trump received".
How did that work out?
Kelly's trying to do the same thing three months later.
He may emerge as a more effective leader than Priebus, but Trump is still in his impulsive state, and his aides are still vying for influence.
These immutable factors will make Kelly's task very difficult.
