Researchers have now revealed that the first find of an incredible creature the size of a rhinoceros, discovered by a Canadian miner, is so well preserved that experts have dubbed it the "Mona Lisa of the dinosaurs".
It was so well preserved that they could tell that the pul pul pul was reddish brown in color and had a 'problematic past'.
A report in Current Biology described it as 'the best preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the best dinosaur species on earth.'
The fossil is a newly discovered species of nodosaur that lived from the mid-Cretaceous period to 110 to 112 million years ago.
Its remarkably well-preserved state has astonished researchers, who describe it as 'really magnificent.'
The plant-eating armored is the best-preserved fossil of its kind, according to reports in National Geographic.
It was discovered by Shawn Funk on March 21, 2011 while he was digging the Suncor Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in Northern Alberta, Canada.
He hit something that looked strange to him in the rock around him and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil that was recovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
They spent the next six years extracting the beast from 2,500 pounds of dirt.
After all this hard work, the finished product is now ready to be presented.
Lead author Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum where the creature is on display, said, "If you squint your eyes a little, you can almost believe it's asleep".
'It will go down in scientific history as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur species, the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.'
Examining its skin, researchers found that this plant-eater, though armored and resembling a walking tank, was likely facing a serious threat from the flesh-eating dinosaurs.
The heavily armoured dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a protective technique known as counter-shadowing, which many modern animals use.
Experts suggest that it was hunted by larger dinosaurs, which allowed it to blend in better with its environment and outrun its enemies.
The 110-million-year-old creature from the nodosaur family first made headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
The researchers have now finished their work and named the wild animal Borealopelta markmitchelli, in honor of museum technician Mark Mitchell, who was part of the team that spent more than 7,000 hours laboriously trying to find it.
The species' remarkable preservation has enabled Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the seals and the armor on the body.
They discovered countershading, a common defense method in the animal kingdom, which means that the creature's upper body is darker on the underside.
Although contra-shading is common, the findings are surprising because Borealopelta's size far outstrips any contra-shaded animal alive today.
This means that the dinosaur was sufficiently oppressed and hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution chose to hide as a method of survival rather than face it.
But most modern animals that use counter shading (such as deer, zebras, or armadillos) are much smaller and more prone to being a prey, meaning that this nodeor has faced a serious challenge to survive.
'The powerful predation of a large, heavily armoured animal 'shows just how dangerous the Cretaceous dinosaur predators could be,' said Brown.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds in their fur also revealed that the dinosaur's skin was reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal for clues about its life, including its preserved intestinal contents, to find out what it ate for its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into a river and was swept away into the sea, where it sank back to the ocean surface.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as South Florida is today, and the rivers and oceans probably extended much further inland than they do now.
"The Nodozor is remarkable in that it is completely covered and protected by a fur coat, and also in that the original shape of the animal is preserved in a three-dimensional way", Brown said.
'And then, the animal looks almost exactly the same today as it did in the early Cretaceous.
You don't need much imagination to rebuild it; if you close your eyes a little, you can almost believe that it's asleep.'
The Cretaceous was when giant theropods, flesh-eating dinosaurs that stood on two feet, roamed the Earth.
Although he was king of them all, Tyrannosaurus rex lived millions of years after the armored dinosaur Borealopelta, which may have been hunted by some of its formidable ancestors.
Among them is the Acrocanthosaurus, a 38 ft (11.5 m) long, 6 tonnes (6 short tons) monster.
Scientists whose latest findings appear in the journal Current Biology believe that Borealopelta was washed out to sea and mummified in mud after it died.
