As Ferrell drove to Ferguson with his daughter, who wore a floral dress and wore a tailored crown, they returned that morning to the "talk about the black experience and the black condition" they had repeatedly spoken of.
"Remember when I taught you that black people should fight for what they believe in?"
"We're going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old kid, and it wasn't true.
I couldn't resist buying it", Ferrell said later.
"What is happening here today... is the result of what happened in the past.
He has to know it, see it, and grow into it.
Not only should we be able to advance in the realm of activism and organizing, but we should also know the layers of the black experience and the black condition and what we need to do to liberate ourselves, to liberate ourselves.
Even if I'm lucky enough to give her an experience where she doesn't have to experience the gross racism in person, she's no different than any other black woman-child.
I feel that I am doing him harm by protecting him from them".
When they got to Ferguson, their first stop was on South Florissant Road, which became a sort of campground for activists, where they waited for the police to come in and talk about the issue, which ultimately resulted in Officer Darren Wilson not being charged.
