They prepared the bags and helped to deliver them to the protesters.
A new brand of activism was slowly taking shape for Ferrell.
She said that as a student at Missouri State University, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association and focused on food justice and health inequities in the black community, saying, "My activism has completely changed since 9/11.
"I had no experience in organizing.
It just came out".
Weeks later, Ferrell met with one of the film's co-directors, Sabaah Folayan, at an evening screening.
Folayan said he and his director, Lucas Alvarado-Farrar, wanted to "document" what happened.
Ferrell had a question in mind: "Do you want to document it or are you trying to find a story that you can use?"
This skepticism was expressed by a multitude of people, mostly white, who came to a community to profit from its pain and its resistance.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, "We heard that the voices of people born and raised in Ferguson were not concentrated, and we decided to do it differently".
Folayan, a local artist known for his activism on death row, had already contacted co-director Damon Davis.
His involvement inspired Ferrell to the project, as did the other six area residents who made up the "Whose Streets?" team in the years after Brown's shooting.
David said, "This documentary is not about someone speaking for us or speaking to us; we are the ones speaking".
"That was the key to me, how these people would be represented because that's how I would be represented".
Folayan said that while the goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences, it proved that the film participants were the most vulnerable, as he showed that the movement was "not about a christian leader, but about a community coming together".
So "Whose Streets?" surprisingly documents the personal aspects of Ferrell's life, including his love affair and marriage to his wife.
Laughing at the first sight of the finished product, Ferrell said, "I felt like naked".
"But I realized that in doing this work and humanizing black people, there could be a certain amount of sensitivity".
Also, Ferrell's story solidifies and re-centers the role of black lesbian women in the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement, who took to social media to spread the hashtag #BlackLivesMatter after the 2012 murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin, identify themselves as gay.
"Black lesbian women in leadership have sustained the movement in general", Ferrell said, "and that's because we've been constantly fighting on many fronts.
Black lesbians have to bear the brunt of it".
Folayan added: "The movement is really being sustained by black women and by many gay black women".
Still, Ferrell insists that "this is nothing like affirmative action" and that he was not elected because of his identities.
"He was the one who set this energy into motion", he says.
"But it's no accident that she's on the front lines, because as a black, gay woman, there's a lot to lose living a life at these intersections.
You can feel his energy on the screen".
By the way, news cameras in Ferguson are long gone, but there are still some disturbing racial connections between the community and the police.
Ferrell's on probation for another two and a half years for blocking the highway during a demonstration.
He describes the socio-political atmosphere in the area he calls home as "a mess".
Yet, Ferguson is still remembering the song he memorized three years ago when he took to the streets.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
Winning is our job.
We should love and support each other.
