A reasonable analogy: The artist uses Chelsea Manning's DNA to create portraits
In the center of the room at the Friedman Gallery in New York, there are many faces, white, black and brown, dangling from the ceiling wires, each one almost indistinctly resembling the other.
This is a 30-portrait by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg, made from earrings and hair clippings sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Former intelligence analyst Manning, who is serving a 35-year sentence for leaking classified diplomatic messages via the WikiLeaks website, reportedly sent his haircut from Fort Leavenworth prison.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called A Fitting Resemblance.
It's the product of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her discipline with expertise in technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a trans woman whose sentence was commuted by Barack Obama three days before her term ended.
By algorithmically analyzing the DNA extracted from Manning and creating 30 portraits of what a person with this gene data might look like, Dewey-Hagborg revealed not only the machinability of the DNA data (that there are many ways it can be interpreted and the determinism of interpretations that comes from the essence) but also its identity with a tight, perhaps somewhat cerebral interpretation.
Manning, who was born Edward Bradley but openly identified as a woman in her teens, was convicted in 2013 of 20 felony counts, including six counts under the Espionage Act, computer fraud, and theft.
The image was pressed by the prison so that it had only one photograph: a black and white portrait of Manning, who was apparently restless, sitting in the driver's seat, wearing a platinum-yellow wig that identified with him.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg was making a breakthrough with the huge success of her 2012 project, The Stranger Things.
In this, the artist created portraits by sifting through DNA from the waste of legal items like cigarette butts and chewing gum to create a picture of what these people might look like.
Just then, she got an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They were doing an interview with Chelsea Manning while she was in prison and they wanted some sort of portrait to accompany this piece", explained Dewey-Hagborg at the press preview of the new exhibition.
And he couldn't be visited or photographed, so they reached out to Chelsea and asked if she'd be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and his imprisoned inspiration became unexpected correspondents, exchanging many letters over a two-year period.
They even released Repressed Imagery, a comic book illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, in which the president forgives Chelsea's sentence and imagines a future in which she can personally see the exhibit.
It was a happy coincidence that Obama actually called for Manning's release a few days after the book came out, which came well after seven harrowing years in a military prison in Kansas.
As Donald Trump finds new, tweetable ways to wage war on government leakers and transgender soldiers and further fuel the sharp divisions he's been asked to fix, there's something deep and powerful about this exhibit that's just being unveiled.
When asked about the odd timing of all this, Dewey-Hagborg said, "Things happen for a reason".
An artist's statement written on the gallery wall, with Manning's signature in large letters underneath (the "i" in his name is punctuated with a heart), called for an end to "automatic discrimination" based on "gender, race, sexuality and culture".
On the wall is her mitochondrial DNA sequence: lots of C's, G's and A's written in pencil...
By including the 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist's sophisticated science dictionary), Dewey Hagborg wanted to convey how we are all, at least as biological creatures, amazingly similar.
"What I hope people take away from this is that our genome doesn't care about who we are and how open the interpretation of genetic data is, how subjective it is", said Dewey-Hagborg, who is exhibiting his 2007 video work, Imitation Memories.
"DNA data can tell many different stories, and this is 30 of those stories".
The last piece in the exhibition, which is held in a single room, is a page from the short comic book I mentioned earlier.
Here is Manning, King Kong style, coming out of the United States Disciplinary Barracks with a speaker.
"They win if they silence your conversation".
"So never shut up".
The artist from Philadelphia said, "This came directly from a letter he wrote to me".
"I still get tingly hair when I talk about it".
Manning has not yet seen the exhibit in person (as he's quite predictably dreamed of from the cartoon book), but when he does, he'll be greeted by masks, his own genetic imitations, who have gathered like a group of protesters in the middle of the room.
Like everything in the exhibit, the genetic haplogroups were written in pencil up to Manning's height, which was specially made.
Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits, "In the past I would put them on the wall, but I wanted them to feel like a crowd".
"I wanted it to be seen as a collective movement, "which was also the movement behind his release, "formed with Chelsea".
