Startups that will help your company not be the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure employee happiness at an e-commerce start-up, but the surveys weren't working.
The answers were often vague, unhelpful, or worse, misleading.
Even if he had pledged anonymity, some of the staff didn't trust him.
"It's never been consistent or objective", says Errett, who runs Madison Reed, a 75-person e-commerce company in San Francisco that specializes in hair care.
So he called outside help.
A new kind of human resources startup is emerging to help companies understand how their employees feel.
They're building and licensing software that specifically measures employee engagement, allowing companies to conduct random surveys, target specific teams and demographics, offer employees anonymity and complaint hotlines, and in some cases, allow employees to report a malpractice bypassing senior management and going directly to the board of directors.
"There are now tools that monitor your health like Strava and Fitbit, but where is your company's Fitbit?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Glint, a Redwood City startup that measures employee engagement by software analytics tools.
Errett says that by using Glint, he's better able to understand what his employees are thinking and feeling three years later.
It offers specific teams snapshots and elective polls, and a heat map that shows which departments of the company receive the most complaints and a glimpse of which managers have low approval ratings, so that the reasons for these can be tinkered with.
Companies are beginning to understand that in order to not become the next Uber, they need to be aware of the culture of their workplace, which has been in a state of scandal ever since a former Uber employee described a harassment environment in a blog post where those who speak their minds openly are punished.
For startups like Glint, this need for surveillance means a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the financial technology insights website Let's Talk Payments, the global governance, regulation and compliance industry could be worth $118.7 billion by 2020.
Interest and activity in Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies detect and block misconduct, has increased amid the Uber discrediting controversy earlier this year.
Convercent has close to 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft, and Tesla.
Uber recently signed up as a customer.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to conduct personalized "subs" surveys, collect real-time, unclassified responses, and extract heat maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous tip line where employees can report misconduct.
If the president is indicted, complaints go directly to the board.
Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Covercent, said, "The courtroom has taken control of the organizers".
Quinlan said that if a company is unethical or bad with its employees, it could face costly consequences from consumer boycotts, worker strikes, or lawsuits, even without regulators stepping in.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with over 25,000 employees, has been using Convercent for over a year to make sure that employees are aware of the policies and procedures and provide easy access to the corporate headquarters.
Previously, when an employee wanted to report a problem, they had to find a phone number or email address for the company's headquarters, file an official complaint, and hope it would be taken seriously.
James Vitrano, Ruby Tuesday's chief legal counsel, said that these are often frightening and disturbing experiences, and that it's not a good way to follow up on employee complaints.
But now, with the company's use of Convercent, problems that were previously hidden from managers in remote offices, cities, or states (such as discrimination, harassment, or unfair pay practices) can be detected and resolved much more quickly.
"I can get even closer to this whole, 360-degree view of the employment experience", said Vitrano, who heads Ruby Tuesday's risk management group.
"We also protect our shareholders from business lawsuits".
After the accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed in 2002 due to ethical violations stemming from the Enron scandal, companies took their ethics, values and employee relations more seriously in 2002, Quinlan said.
But after social media came to its senses, companies realized they couldn't keep their dirty laundry from going viral.
"Before technology was used to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy".
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service and charge recurring fees for the use of their products.
It's a business model and an opportunity that has the endorsement of venture capitalists who support both of these start-ups.
Convercent received $10 million in funding in February from firms including Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing its total capital to $47 million.
Glint raised $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November, bringing his total funding to $60 million.
Given the interconnected nature of companies, their cultures and their venture capital, these investments are not surprising.
Research on the increase in volume shows that today's employees expect more from their workplace than in the past.
In competitive markets like Silicon Valley, high salaries and interesting projects are just the minimum requirements.
Employees want to feel accepted, valued and giving their time to a company with a positive mission.
Nina McQueen, LinkedIn's vice president of global benefits and employee experience, who uses both Convercent and Glint, said, "When people are happy to be in a company, feel like their voices are being heard, and feel good about the work they do, they're more committed to making that company succeed".
Investors make money when their portfolio companies do well; companies do well when their employees are genuine and feel they belong.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee engagement and sense of belonging, it's no surprise that they're finding support.
Having data on employee loyalty is important to workplace culture experts.
But the data is useless unless the company's leaders act.
In fact, if a company asks for feedback from its employees, it can create an expectation that change is coming.
And if the expectation doesn't come quickly enough, or not at all, it can cause frustration and leave employees feeling disconnected.
Russell Raath, who is the head of consulting at Kotter International, a business management firm, and who has seen the mistake of firms relying too much on data collection, said, "If you're going to ask for 4,000 suggestions, you have to be prepared for 4,000 talks".
"Because if you don't follow up, the staff will think, 'Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why should I?'"
According to Errett, Madison Reed, who did the monthly employee surveys, was able to take action the same day when a problem was reported in Glint.
And after collecting feedback from employees who were tired of the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, he was able to reorganize various teams within the company and add communication training to solve problems.
On Ruby Tuesday, the company gets new insights about its employees, and hopes that in the long run this will translate into being able to retain more workers in this kind of industry where there's a high number of employees coming in and out.
Vitrona said, "If you're not committed to creating a culture of transparency, you're going to lose people".
"And if you lose people, you're going to lose customers.
And when you lose customers, you're going to lose businesses".
