Facebook increases the power of verifying stories to combat fake news
Facebook will send more potential fake articles to third-party story-checkers and show their findings under original sharing, the world's largest online social network said Thursday as it tries to combat so-called fake news.
In a statement on the company's website, it said that they will use updated machine learning to detect possible fraud and send them to story checkers, potentially showing the story check results below the original article.
Facebook has been criticized for being one of the main distribution points for what many believe to be fake news that influenced the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
The issue has become a major political issue in Europe as well, with French voters facing a flood of fake news ahead of the presidential election in May, and Germany backing a plan to impose penalties on social media networks if they fail to quickly remove hateful posts before the elections in September.
In a separate statement in German on Thursday, Facebook said that a test of the new story validation feature was being launched in the US, France, the Netherlands and Germany.
Sara Su, Facebook's news stream product manager, said in a blog post, "In addition to seeing which stories are being discussed by third-party story validators, people want more resources about what they're reading and sharing to make informed decisions".
He added that Facebook would continue to test the "relevant articles" feature and work on other changes to the news feed to reduce fake news.
Creating a comic: the story of a castle in England
In its recent history, the tiny Scotney Castle featured in a Squeeze music video and became a refuge for Margaret Thatcher in the 1970s and 1980s.
But now, with sweep-edged hair and a penchant for historical documentation, Scotney, who inspired a comic book by Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshireman, has witnessed 700 years of tumultuous history from his comfortable chair in the valley of the River Bewl in Kent.
"I find it fascinating to look at the handwriting of someone who's been dead for 300 years", he says sympathetically.
"What a personal connection to have this letter in my hand".
A Castle in England, stretching from Edwardian times to the Middle Ages, each story documents families who lived in Scotney to be painted by a different artist named from the United Kingdom (Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg).
This is not Rhodes' first book based on an archive: he also wrote Toothless Men and Other Stories in 2014, a project he found unexpectedly emotional, inspired by stories in the British Library.
"I was even struck by the fingerprint on the margin of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the King James supporters".
"That was his thumbprint!
And letters always smell of ice because you used to light a fire for the light.
For someone 300 years from now, that smell makes him feel like he's there, too.
Oh, I love the records!"
As a paper lover, getting support from the National Trust and the Arts Council of England and staying in a castle for almost four months ("To be honest, I've over-received my warm welcome a little bit".) seems too good.
Rhodes spent his days exploring the "new" Victorian castle, sifting through archives and studying many treasures and antiques, such as the hyenas' heads mounted on the walls of the mansion and bottles that had been in the trenches for centuries.
He toured the grounds and ruins of the old castle, talking to guards, gardeners, and sometimes artists working on illustrations for his book.
Then at night, he'd "drink whiskey and write".
The National Trust only had full access to the details of Scotney's history when the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, died in 2006.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff had just begun to seize the archive, which he describes as "the centuries-old aristocracy saying, 'Oh, throw him in the attic.'"
Diaries, letters from the days of the British empire, maps that marked the boundaries of who owned what: "You'd think land disputes would be boring", says Rhodes, "but there was a beech tree that the two families were fighting over.
Let it go, people!"
Some stories in the collection, including The Labourer, who left the newly built castle to join the Peasants' Revolt in 1381, use the castle as a jumping-off point for a wider introduction to English history.
"In this book, The Households of the Knights of Kent and Sussex, there is a record of a rebellion in the castle in 1380", says Rhodes.
"The Peasant's Rebellion had begun around here, and I thought a rebellion might be a good place to start.
Maybe the two are connected?"
Other stories are closely linked to the castle's history, such as The Priest, which tells the story of the Darrell family hiding a Jesuit priest for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler, which features 18th-century smuggler Arthut Darrell, who is thought to have filled a coffin with stones and staged his own funeral.
The Darrells were Rhodes' favourite Scotney family: "These gentlemen seemed quite a crook, always going into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darrell men have solved debt crises by marrying rich old women; I imagine them as a bunch of handsome men who have a knack for courting female heirs".
With his stint on the street over, Rhodes is looking for more solo writing experience.
In the Finnish wild, he completed a two-week work on a comic about Elämänmäki, the site of a sanatorium in the early 20th century, which has since been reclaimed by nature.
But Scotney holds a special place in his heart.
"I was sad to be separated", he says.
"Like, 'Oh, now I have to go and face the fucking real world.' "
