Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can alleviate IBS.
Red meat and chocolate may sound like a nightmare for your digestive system.
But a new study claims the opposite: A diet rich in meat-based protein and dairy products may help alleviate symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable medical condition, which affects 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, causes stomach cramps and bloating, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Although patients are often advised to skip meat and dairy to alleviate their symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington have found that the protein's main amino acid, tryptophan, helps develop immune cells that develop a resilient gut.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells patrol the intestines to prevent foodborne germs from sneaking into the body.
Cells that are capable of triggering inflammation are balanced by cells that promote endurance by protecting delicate tissues from damage.
If the balance shifts too much towards inflammation, it can result in inflammatory bowel disease.
In experiments, mice that carried a specific bacterium in their intestines were found to have developed a type of immune cell that promoted endurance.
And bacteria need tryptophan, one of the building blocks of protein, to trigger the appearance of cells.
Professor Colonna said: 'We have linked the development of a cell population that promotes resistance to the bacterium Lactobacillus reuteri, a species that is part of the gut microbiome.'
Mice that had more tryptophan in their diet had more of these immune cells.'
If the same thing is happening in humans, L. reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan could develop a more resilient, less inflammatory gut environment.
While working on a type of immune cell that enhances endurance, postdoctoral researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas discovered that one group of lab mice had this type of cell, but another group of mice of the same species, held in a different location, did not.
He suspected that the difference was related to the mice's gut microbiome, or the communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The intestines of the mice were sequenced, and the mice with immune cells had six different types of bacteria, but the mice without them had none.
Mice lacking an intestinal microbiome and not developing this type of immune cell because they were raised in a sterile environment were given L. reuteri and the immune cells emerged.
To understand how the bacterium affects the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in liquid and then transferred small amounts of this liquid, which was free of bacteria, to immature immune cells taken from mice.
The immune cells have been transformed into cells that promote endurance.
It turns out that the active ingredient is a byproduct of the metabolism of tryptophan, known as indole-3-lactic acid, when purified from the liquid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's food, the number of cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan said that humans have cells that promote the same endurance as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is unknown whether tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri develop in humans as they do in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
He said, "The development of these cells is something we probably want to encourage because these cells control inflammation in the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially, the high levels of tryptophan in the cases where L. reuteri is present, cause the population to spread".
