The White House Show cost the taxpayers thousands
According to military records released to TIME, the White House's decision last month to fly a Marine helicopter over the southern grass for an organization that promotes American manufacturing has cost taxpayers a staggering $24,000.
When the president boarded, the green and white Sikorsky VH-3D, also known as Marine One, was the focus of attention at the July 17th U.S. build program introduction at the White House.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials toured products made in all 50 states.
A Connecticut-made helicopter, a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi were displayed side by side.
According to records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter, the White House War Department requested the helicopter's availability by a special order (also called FRAGO) just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the southern grass for "extraordinary" organization.
The commander of HMX-1 sent an email to his superior, the Deputy Commandant of the Marine Air Corps, the day before the organization, saying, "I just wanted to make sure you were aware because this is an unusually high-visibility organization".
The message said the helicopter would arrive at the south lawn at about 7 a.m. on July 17 for the 3 p.m. organization and stay there until the lawn was cleaned between 6 and 9 p.m.
The memo added that if the White House departure was delayed, a second flight crew would be needed for the return flight due to duty time limitations.
The unit's security personnel were inside the aircraft while it was on the ground, while the original flight crew was in the helicopter during the organizing.
It's unclear from the records provided to TIME whether a second flight crew was ultimately necessary.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
The records show that HMX-1 is investigating whether the organization violated this provision.
The commander wrote, "One question we asked was whether he had violated the Hatch Act, and we were told he had not".
"Looks like you're locked in", the Deputy Commander said.
Made in America is designated as a formal organization by the White House and is not subject to the Hatch Act.
But even formal organizations have political implications.
The president of the organization noted the ongoing health care reform efforts in the Senate at the time and praised the efforts to tighten government regulations.
The use of aircraft, known as Marine One or Air Force One, for politically advantageous purposes is not a new phenomenon.
Presidents are supposed to use these to travel.
But it's unusual for these to be officially requested for use only for a photo opportunity.
Trump came to attention in February when the presidential plane was taken behind the scenes at the first campaign rally in Melbourne Florida, and his Twitter account was filled with messages about his predecessor's use of the presidential plane.
"The White House is excited about the 'Made in America' exhibit, where products made with American materials by American workers from all 50 states are on display", said Lindsay Walters, deputy press secretary.
The HMX-1 crew frequently makes training flights over the Washington area and rehearses on the south lawn to drop the President of the United States at the White House with a point-blank shot.
While in Germany for the G-20 summit in early July, Trump made 58 practice landings at the White House on HMX-1.
An official said the flight for Made in America was part of the aircrew's training needs for that month.
The unit's helicopters flew an additional 11 hours that day for "support duties not related to the presidency".
The White House says taxpayers aren't charged for any other numbers in the organization.
A spokesman for Sikorksky said the company was not involved in arranging for the helicopter to be displayed on the south lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights and it is difficult to determine the exact cost incurred by the organization.
But according to the Department of Defense's hourly rates for the 2017 fiscal year, the Department of Defense's rate of coverage for the VH-3D is $24,340 per flight hour.
Unit logs record the aircraft's flight time as 30 minutes each way from the Marine Corps Air Facility headquarters in Quantico, Virginia.
The White House claims the actual operating cost of the helicopter is far below that rate.
"It is very misleading to impose a cost on taxpayers based on estimates of cost-to-income ratios", said Walters.
"These estimates include sunk costs in personnel, maintenance and annual expenses".
According to a 2015 RAND study, the Department of Defense's expense-reimbursement rates do not include personnel costs, but include fuel, maintenance and contract costs.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer advocated the use of the helicopter for this organization.
Spicer said, "The idea here is to show what's made in America this week".
"And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of their contributions to our national security, and I suspect that hundreds if not thousands of people are working on this.
And I think we're all very proud of the helicopters and other military equipment that so many Americans, like so many Americans, have worked tirelessly to make.
So of course it's appropriate to highlight this".
It's unclear if Trump interacted with the helicopter while touring the south lawn for the organization, but he stepped into the driver's seat of a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump joked with the media about the company's products in his own fleet, and called out Sikorsky's representatives.
"I know Sikorsky very well", said the president, "and I have three of them".
