Interpol has six Europeans on its list of deadly bombs.
The German newspaper Die Welt reported that Interpol (the International Police Organization) sent a list of 173 names of people with the potential to carry out suicide attacks on behalf of the terrorist organization DEAŞ to the security agencies in European countries last May.
132 people on the list were reportedly from Iraq, North Africa, the Gulf countries, Tajikistan and Bangladesh.
Six of the people on the list were identified as European citizens.
The individuals are said to be from Germany, Belgium, France, the Netherlands and Bosnia.
The suspected DEAŞ contact from Germany is a 27-year-old German citizen from Solingen, North Rhine Westphalia.
It was stated that the person went to Egypt first, then Turkey, and finally to Syria in the autumn of 2012.
In mid-July, ISIS announced on its social media accounts that this person had died in Rakhine.
The German Security Agency has not responded to the newspaper's questions on the matter.
It was claimed that the names on Interpol's list were captured in Mosul during operations against Daesh.
According to Die Welt, the American intelligence services examined the list and sent it to Interpol.
Interpol reportedly passed the list to police agencies across Europe in May.
Die Welt reported that the German security circles believe that ISIS may be trying to send some of the names on this list to Europe to organize suicide attacks.
